<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-581-519  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 581 519.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  April 1989 v21 n4 p26(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Beware the hazards of showing off. (EDP and the law) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mersich, Dan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>If a user buys a number of IBM clones for improved priceperformance, is it illegal for him to attach a phony IBM label onthe microcomputer at the front desk to impress customers? Theissue may appear to be an open and shut case of copyrightinfringement under Canadian law.andP;  However, since the purpose ofthe fraud is merely to impress, rather than to sell the equipment,the question may bear some legal question.andP;  Under the law, thecourts would have to define the term 'make use of' within thestatues in order to decide the issue.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Legal IssuesIntellectual PropertyComputer CrimesPrivate LabelCanadaThird-Party Vendors.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>